subsection.p:
Thinking of gas as a thermodynamic system and the spring as its environment, we state this observation using the principle of the conservation of energy as follows.

	\Delta E_\text{of gas} =  -W_\text{by gas} = \text{Energy exchanged with environment.}

Here, we see the exchange of energy occur through the performance of a mechanical work. Next we will see another mechanism of exchange of energy.

Once again, we can state this observation as a conservation of energy statment. Think of the gas as the thermodynamic system and the water bath as the environment, then we have
\Delta E_\text{gas} = Q_\text{into gas} = \text{Energy exchanged with environment.}
Here, we saw the mechanism of exchange of energy was not through a mechanical work but through heat.

solution.p:
(b)  

For the a-b process:

	\left.
	\begin{array}{l}
		W_{ab} = 0\\
		Q_{ab} = 3,600\ \text{J}
	\end{array}
	\right\}
	\ \ \ U_{ab} = Q_{ab} - W_{ab} = 3,600\ \text{J}.

For the b-c process:

	\left.
	\begin{array}{l}
		W_{bc}   = 2,026\ \text{J}\\
		Q_{bc} = 2,400\ \text{J}
	\end{array}
	\right\}
	\ \ \ U_{bc} = Q_{bc} - W_{bc} = 374\ \text{J}.

subsection.p:
Joule conducted experiments on the effect of stirring on the change in the state of water as determined from the change in the temperature of water. He found that, if the container is thermally insulated, the amount of work associated with the change of the state of water was independent of how the work was performed. 

	W_{if} = U_f - U_i \ \ \ \text{(Adiabatic)}

This is what you expect from the first law of thermodynamics when  Q = 0. The work here is also called   adiabatic work. The adiabatic work can be used to find internal energy of a system with respect to a reference state, called the  standard state.
